Note: difference between Abstract class and Interface
      Abstract class: Use when classes share a common base
      and you want shared state + shared implementation.
      It can have "fields", "constructors", and both "abstract" and "concrete" methods.
      A class can extend only one abstract class.

      Interface: Use to define a contract/capability that
      many unrelated classes can implement.
      Typically no instance state or constructors (only constants).
      Supports default/static methods.
      A class can implement multiple interfaces.